## Import, Clean and Save Dataset
This notebook uses the Netflix Movies and Shows dataset to show the following processes.
1. Importing csv data
2. Looking at the inferred schema - eg. what does Spark believe the value type of each column represents
3. Creating temporary views (eg. `CREATE view netflix_raw`)
4. Using Spark SQL interpreter to view the loaded table
5. Understanding DataFrame schemas (Schema Inference and Declarative Schemas)

import spark.implicits._
import org.apache.spark.sql._
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._

val BaseFilePath = "file:///learn"
val NetflixTitlesRaw = "/netflix/netflix_titles_raw.csv"
val NetflixTitlesFormatted = "/netflix/netflix_titles.csv"

val netflixData = spark.read
  //.option("mode", "FAILFAST | DROPMALFORMED")
  .option("header", "true")
  .option("inferSchema", "true")
  .option("encoding", "UTF-8")
  .csv(s"$BaseFilePath/$NetflixTitlesFormatted")

// see the underlying inferredSchema
netflixData.printSchema
val inferredSchema = netflixData.schema
netflixData.createOrReplaceTempView("netflix_raw")
spark.sql("show tables").show

The ability to easily group your data across new dimensions enables you to be a better explorer of your data.
1. What is interesting to you? I think the ability to groupBy year/month/day and by categroy could be nice
2. Let us add a target DateTime column as well as year, month, day to our initial DataFrame.
3. We also should extract out the Numeric values for the duration of the netflix content. We can use this to isolate content of similar length - either number of seasons or length of content.
4. Also we will need to look for potentially corrupt or null data, and decide what to do with it.

paragraphs.text:
%spark

val netflixWithTimeDimension = netflixDataStrict
  .withColumn("duration_type",
    when(col("type").equalTo("Movie"), 0)
    .otherwise(1))
  .withColumn("duration_numeric",
    when(col("type").equalTo("Movie"), regexp_replace(col("duration"), "\\ min", ""))
    .otherwise(regexp_replace(col("duration"), "\\Season|\\Seasons", ""))
    .cast("Double"))
  .withColumn("datetime", functions.to_timestamp(
      trim(col("date_added")), "MMMMM dd, yyyy")
      )
  .withColumn("release_month", functions.date_format(col("datetime"), "M")
  .cast("Double"))
  .withColumn("release_day", functions.date_format(col("datetime"), "d")
  .cast("Double"))

// leaning on spark's ability to generate and use the Data Description Language (DDL) enables us 
// to use the 'steal-the-schema' pattern. Which can be used to define a strict schema for extraction from a Redis Hash
// in later places
val newTableDDL = netflixWithTimeDimension.schema.toDDL

## Let us inspect the data using Redis CLI
1. Open up a new terminal window. `docker exec -it redis5 redis-cli`
2. View all of the Keys. `keys *`
3. Take a look at the Serialized Size of the Data. `debug object netflix_norm:80123742` and `debug object netflix:80123742`
4. If you want to remove all keys `flushall`. Note: Flushall will delete everything and let you start over
